The gallant soldier’s demise showed Kenyans, first hand, the real risks frontline workers face in caring for Coronavirus patients. 






Dr Doreen Lugaliki, who succumbed to Covid-19.
Photo credit: File | Nation Media Group

 

Dr Lugaliki’s colleagues praised her for giving her life in the line of duty, terming her July 13, 2020 burial date as “Black Monday”. 

"We as a family will greatly miss the laughter our daughter created and the united she always brought to the family," her mother said, weeping. 

Doreen was set to marry Mr Fred Mboss this year. Mr Mboss’ family was awaiting easing of travel restrictions to kick-start dowry negotiations. Captain Daudi Kibati and Captain Salah Salim Jeizan 

When Kenya Airways offered to fly home Kenyans stranded in the United States for free, the noble act largely fell on Mr Daudi Kibati’s shoulders. 

The 61-year-old retired Kenya Airforce Major, ranked as captain at KQ, flew the Dreamliner 787 that brought home several Kenyans stranded in one of the cities hit hardest by the Coronavirus. 



