The flight from the John F. Kennedy Airport was to be the last of KQ’s fleet to evacuate Kenyans. Unfortunately, it would also be Mr Kibati’s last. 

Mr Kibati landed the plane at the Jomo Kenyatta International Airport on March 24. He proceeded into quarantine at the Ole Sereni Hotel in Nairobi alongside his first officer. 

Five days later, Mr Kibati tested positive for Coronavirus. 

The disease showed him no mercy, as Mr Kibati succumbed three days after testing positive. 






Captain Daudi Kimuyu Kibati. PHOTO | COURTESY

 

Unbeknown to the airline, they would lose another pilot to Covid-19 eight months later. 

57-year-old captain Salah Salim Jeizan succumbed to the disease on December 2 in a London hospital where he was receiving treatment. 

In November captain Jeizan developed breathing difficulties at his hotel in London. Preceding that, he had flown his aircraft from Jomo Kenyatta International Airport to Heathrow Airport in London. He was rushed to the hospital and put on oxygen. 

After a month long admission, the captain unfortunately succumbed, and was buried in London under Islamic law. The senior captain had joined the national carrier in 2001 as a junior pilot, rising to the position of a senior captain on the Boeing 787 fleet. Dr Stephen Mogusu 



