Peres Jepchirchir 

Peres Jepchirchir set two women-only world records, highlighted by her run of one hour, five minutes and six seconds in winning gold for Kenya at the World Athletics Half Marathon Championships in Gdynia, Poland, in October. 

Jepchirchir, the 2016 winner, regained her world title in a dramatic race that saw defending champion Netsanet Gudeta and world record-holder Yeshaneh both fall by the wayside. 






Peres Jepchirchir of Kenya reacts after beating the World Record (1:05:16) and wins the women's race of the 2020 IAAF World Half Marathon Championships in Gdynia, Poland, in October 17, 2020.
Photo credit: Mateusz Slodkowski | AFP

 

On December 6, Jepchirchir stepped up from the half marathon to the full marathon, winning the Valencia Marathon in 2:17:16 to move to seventh on the world all-time list.  

Superb performances given that 2020 saw virtually all athletics competitions cancelled and athletes having to train minimally while observing Covid-19 protocols. 

Health CS Mutahi Kagwe 

Ever since Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe announced Kenya’s first Coronavirus case on March 13, the bureaucrat has ensured Kenyans get daily updates on the pandemic. 

He was exactly two weeks into the job when Kenya confirmed its first Coronavirus case. 

Only in September did Mr Kagwe start delegating the duty to juniors. He only comes in when he has a big announcement to make 

Mr Kagwe’s animated and emotional communication panache in daily briefings, coupled with his leadership style have given Kenyans hope in the face of the pandemic. 



