Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe gives an update at Afya House in Nairobi on the Covid-19 pandemic in Kenya, on November 16, 2020. 
Photo credit: Dennis Onsongo | Nation Media Group

 

“His traits became assets,” one publication said of him. 

Whenever he took to the podium to give the briefings, Mr Kagwe would hilariously persuade Kenyans using all manner of messaging, including songs. 






With this he was listed by the Wall Street Journal among effective leaders globally during the coronavirus pandemic, the only leader in Africa. Health Director General Patrick Amoth 

The man behind the curtain. The engine that allows a car to run. 

Dr Patrick Amoth handles all technical issues at the Ministry of Health. 

His engagement with Kenyans through Twitter have earned him public endearment, as he answers any questions fired his way. 

Dr Amoth co-chairs the National Emergency Response Committee on Coronavirus that deliberate, projects numbers and advises President Uhuru Kenyatta on the way forward. 

He was among Kenyans who were awarded the Presidential Order of Service Award, Uzalendo Award, for his contribution in the fight against Coronavirus. 

And it was not just Kenyans that noticed his hard work. On May 23, the World Health Organisation appointed Dr Amoth to its executive board as vice chairman. 

At the WHO, Dr Amoth advises and gives effect to the decisions and policies of the World Health Assembly by facilitating the smooth running of the Assembly. He leads 34 peers from different countries. 



