Ms Electine Chausiku Wanyama 

For six years, Ms Electine Chausiku Wanyama has been taking care of vulnerable children living with cerebral palsy and hydrocephalus. 

The former volunteer teacher in a disability center in South Korea visualised starting a similar project in Kenya. 

In 2016, she started Precious Virginia Home. 

The centre is named after her daughter, who died in 2015. The home started in a rented house, but now occupies land donated by Kakamega County. 

The home is at Lairi village in Matungu, along the Mumias-Busia road. 

Ms Wanyama mobilises children living with severe cerebral palsy and hydrocephalus into the home where they can be easily assisted. 

She has also created support groups of parents and guardians where they share experiences and generate resources. 

A single mother of five, Ms Wanyama has no source of income and relies on well-wishers. 

The Home currently houses 35 children from Busia, Bungoma, Vihiga and Kakamega counties. 



