Ms Amina Abdalla 

Over a decade ago, Ms Abdalla started rescuing mentally ill patients from the streets. 

She feeds, clothes and rehabilites them before reuniting them with their parents. 

But when Covid-19 pandemic hit the country, she decided to start an isolation centre specifically for the mentally ill patients. 



if (shouldRenderAd(true)) {
googletag.cmd.push(function () {
googletag.display("mobile-article-ad-8");
});
}




Since May, Ms Abdhalla has rescued over 100 mentally ill patients from various streets in Mombasa and had them tested for Coronavirus. 

Those that tested positive were isolated and cared for before being reunited with their families. 

Not even pressure from some Shanzu residents to close the isolation centre put Ms Abdalla down. 

Ms Abdalla efforts in June got commendation from the Health ministry for making Mombasa the only county to ensure that mentally ill individuals get access to Coronavirus management. 

With around 10 staff including her children and some health workers who volunteered in the initiative, Ms Abdhalla is among Kenya’s heroes. 

Chief Justice David Maraga 

Ever since Justice Maraga rose to the highest echelons of the Judiciary in 2016, the institution has had constant fights with President Uhuru Kenyatta’s administration. 

But Kenya’s second Chief Justice under the 2010 Constitution stood his ground. 

The biggest battle this year, and which completely erased any chance of a Judiciary-Executive handshake, revolved around the appointment of 41 judges to various courts countrywide. 

While President Kenyatta insisted that some of the nominees had been flagged by intelligence agencies, Justice Maraga dared the Executive head to table evidence of misconduct. 



